BMzL6\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"`★ Insight ─────────────────────────────────────`\\nHere's a summary of the architectural choices made across this implementation:\\n\\n1. **Sentinel error pattern** (`ErrEmptyHookInput`): Changed the anonymous `errors.New(\\\"empty hook input\\\")` in the shared `agent` package to an exported sentinel error. This lets the Kiro agent use `errors.Is` to distinguish \\\"no stdin\\\" (expected in IDE mode) from \\\"malformed JSON\\\" (always an error), without changing the behavior for other agents — the error message string is unchanged, so existing string-based test assertions still pass.\\n\\n2. **Data-driven hook definitions** (`ideHookDefs` slice): Rather than hardcoding each IDE hook file's installation logic separately, a `[]ideHookDef` slice maps filename→trigger→CLI verb. This makes the code DRY — `installIDEHooks`, `allIDEHooksPresent`, and `UninstallHooks` all iterate the same slice. Adding a 5th IDE hook later means appending one struct.\\n\\n3. **Layered fallback in lifecycle parsers**: `readHookInputOrEmpty` → `raw.Prompt` → `os.Getenv(\\\"USER_PROMPT\\\")`. Stdin JSON always takes precedence over env vars, so CLI mode behavior is completely unchanged. IDE mode falls through to the env var path.\\n`─────────────────────────────────────────────────`\\n\\nAll 7 tasks are complete. Here's what was implemented:\\n\\n### Changes Summary\\n\\n| File | What Changed |\\n|------|-------------|\\n| `agent/event.go` | Added `ErrEmptyHookInput` sentinel error |\\n| `kiro/types.go` | Added `kiroIDEHookFile`, `kiroIDEHookWhen`, `kiroIDEHookThen` structs |\\n| `kiro/hooks.go` | IDE hook constants, `ideHookDefs`, `installIDEHooks`, `allIDEHooksPresent`, `anyIDEHookPresent`, `isEntireIDEHook` helpers; modified `InstallHooks`/`UninstallHooks`/`AreHooksInstalled` |\\n| `kiro/lifecycle.go` | Added `readHookInputOrEmpty` helper; modified `parseAgentSpawn`/`parseUserPromptSubmit`/`pa